It has become increasingly apparent that different views are not tolerated in the Labour Party, and that every opinion is judged on whether or not it is acceptable by party leadership.
This started shortly after Jeremy took the lead, as the colleagues with whom he thought he shared a similar political perspective began to expect me to turn around and take positions with which I would never agree - either on national security or on the EU single market.
Whenever I speak in public (and it doesn’t really matter what I say), there’s a stream of insults on social media that appeal to the “fire,” denouncing the policies of the center, telling me that I shouldn’t belong to the Labour Party.
And it's not just me who's going through this.
In fact, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, since the comments that are addressed to me tend to be of a political nature.
I am amazed at the professionalism and determination of these colleagues who face a barrage of sexist or racist insults every day, but who never fall back before them.
One of the aspects that most disappoint me in this era of politics is how these levels of insult have become normalized.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we have ceased to be inclusive, and with every motion of “censorship” or change of the rules of selection the party narrows its views.
I have received numerous advice over the past two years urging me to keep my head low, not to be so expressive, and that thus "would be all right" for me.
But that's not why I came here to do politics.
Ever since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student, driven by the negligence of Thatcher’s government that left my school’s classroom literally in ruins, I have sought to fight for better public services for those who need them most, whether as a self-employed person or as a minister in the government.
I never hid my policies, including in the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could have been in any way confused about my political positions and areas of disagreement with the current leadership.
For those who promoted the motion on Friday, all I have to say is that when the country heads for a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on the issue of my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But in fact, the message I have is not for the Nottingham Momentum; it is for my constituents, members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you, and I promise that no threats of "satisfaction" or political files will prevent me from acting in the sense of what I believe are the interests of all of you.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
