North Korea says “don’t think” of a unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continuation of sanctions was worsening distrust toward the United States and that there was no way the country could unilaterally dispense with its nuclear weapons under those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as the interruption of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear testing center and the commitment to non-proliferation of weapons and nuclear technologies.
“However, we don’t see any corresponding U.S. response,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and in such circumstances there is no way we can proceed with our disarmament first.”
Although Ri has recycled North Korean complaints already known about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, within which North Korea would be rewarded as it takes gradual steps, its statements appear to be significant in the extent that they do not reject the unilaterally binding injunctions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between an acting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work towards “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered assurances to North Korea security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States claims Pyongyang has first abandoned its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, opposing even the ‘declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can put us on our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the prolongation of sanctions is worsening our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the party concerned in this matter were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that guiding North Korea’s rockets toward U.S. territory was inevitable after Trump called Kim “the man of the rockets” on a mission in pursuit.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year had threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, filled Kim with praise for his courage to take steps towards disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until the denuclearization denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timetable for such, saying that “if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously until denuclearization is complete, final and verifiable.”
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to tighten the funding of North Korea’s nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the last visit has not been well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, although North Korea later denounced him for "making demands of gangsters."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile facility and also a nuclear complex if the United States "takes appropriate action".
Pompeo said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" they were looking for were the security guarantees Trump had taken in Singapore, as well as initiatives aimed at normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course that teaches them to rest enough
A new course at Harvard University this year put all of its students to sleep more, in an initiative to combat the macho culture of studying in “directs” impregnated with caffeine.
One professor concluded that students at that university at the top of the world ranking often did not have the slightest idea of the most basic concepts about the care they should have with themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration for the course emerged after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you just telling me this in the last year of the course?’
The young woman claimed that no one had ever mentioned to her the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts about how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance, as well as to the improvement of overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the institution decided to introduce the course after concluding that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, shoes and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and about how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine to get to bed.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it won’t change student behavior instantly.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, as we all have the right to know the health effects of the smoking option,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “direct doing” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students makes this a growing problem.
Ensuring that we sleep well enough and with quality should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid getting fatter, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode, making them constantly starved.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler conceive the course after attending one of his classes last year at Harvard.
The course opened his eyes and inspired him to encourage the creation of a course for the entire campus, he said.
The next step, according to your expectations, is to ask all graduate students to attend a similar study program before entering the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider using an alarm for the time to go to bed, such as to wake up, and that they are aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt circadian rhythm and lead to problems.
